problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/linked-list-cycle-ii/description/

Intuition
when i looked at this problem i realized this can be solved using slow and fast pointers , now the key logic is if there is a cycle in linked list and when pointers go inside the loop they meet eventually at a node , so distance from start of cycle node to head and distance from meeting point to start of cycle node is same , so we move slow pointer and a new pointer togetther from meeting point and head and the point where they meet is the start of cycle node .

Approach
initalize slow and fast pointer at head,and fast pointer moves twice the speed of slow pointer then traverse the linked list , if cycle exists then slow and fast pointer meet at a certain point , if slow and fast pointer meets we move another pointer from head with same speed of slow and they both move and when they both meet we reach at start of cycle , hence we return slow , else return none if no cycle exists

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Space complexity:
O(1)
Code
# Definition for singly-linked list.
# class ListNode:
#     def __init__(self, x):
#         self.val = x
#         self.next = None

class Solution:
    def detectCycle(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:
        slow = head
        fast = head
        while fast != None and fast.next != None:
            slow = slow.next
            fast = fast.next.next

            if slow == fast:
                ptr = head
                while slow != ptr:
                    slow = slow.next
                    ptr = ptr.next
                return slow
        return None
